SIMPLE: prevarication
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prevarication
<hw>Pre*var`i*ca"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praevaricatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>pr⟦eacute⟧varication</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of prevaricating, shuffling, or quibbling, to
evade the truth or the disclosure of truth; a deviation from the truth
and fair dealing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The august tribunal of the skies, where no
<qex>prevarication</qex> shall avail.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A secret abuse in the exercise of a public
office.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Roman Law)</fld>
<def>The collusion of an informer with the defendant, for the purpose of
making a sham prosecution.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Common Law)</fld>
<def>A false or deceitful seeming to undertake a thing for the purpose
of defeating or destroying it.</def> <rj><au>Cowell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prevaricator</ent>⟦br⟧
